03924nam a22005295i 9780520920972DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19941994cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209209727 a10.1525/97805209209722doi  a(DE-B1597)648747  a(OCoLC)1419789716  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aPHI0050002bisacsh1 aFarber, Paul Lawrence, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTemptations of Evolutionary Ethics /cPaul Lawrence Farber; ed. by Paul Lawrence Farber. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1994] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Charles Darwin -- t2. Darwinian Ethics -- t3. Evolutionary Ethics: Herbert Spencer -- t4. Darwinian Critics: Thomas Henry Huxley and Alfred Russel Wallace -- t5. Early Reception and Evaluation of Evolutionary Ethics: 1870-1890s -- t6. Evolutionary Baroque and Its Furies: 1890-1920 -- t7. Syntheses, Modern and Otherwise: 1918-1968 -- t8. Evolutionary Ethics Since 1975: Dodo, Phoenix, or Firebird? -- t9. Recapitulation, Lessons, and Queries -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEvolutionary theory tells us about our biological past; can it also guide us to a moral future? Paul Farber's compelling book describes a century-old philosophical hope held by many biologists, anthropologists, psychologists, and social thinkers: that universal ethical and social imperatives are built into human nature and can be discovered through knowledge of evolutionary theory.Farber describes three upsurges of enthusiasm for evolutionary ethics. The first came in the early years of mid-nineteenth century evolutionary theories; the second in the 1920s and '30s, in the years after the cultural catastrophe of World War I; and the third arrived with the recent grand claims of sociobiology to offer a sound biological basis for a theory of human culture.Unlike many who have written on evolutionary ethics, Farber considers the responses made by philosophers over the years. He maintains that their devastating criticisms have been forgotten—thus the history of evolutionary ethics is essentially one of oft-repeated philosophical mistakes.Historians, scientists, social scientists, and anyone concerned about the elusive basis of selflessness, altruism, and morality will welcome Farber's enlightening book.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aEthics & Moral Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh1 aFarber, Paul Lawrence, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021369240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092097240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520920972423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520920972/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles